## Quick Reference

| Command | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `/draft feature\|bug "title"` | Capture a raw idea/bug in the backlog |
| `/plan FEAT-001 [FEAT-002 …]` | Turn draft(s) into ready spec(s); batches questions up front |
| `/implement FEAT-001` | Build a ready spec — tests + code per subtask, then `/verify` |
| `/verify [FEAT-001]` | Feature-done QA: full gate + review + manual smoke |
| `/commit` | Gated conventional commit (runs the canonical `ci.sh fast`) |
| `/release patch\|minor\|major` | Bump + changelog, then run the release/deploy locally |
| `/ship [IDs] \| "topic" [patch\|minor\|major]` | The orchestrator: plan → implement → verify → merge → release |
| `/resume` | Continue interrupted work (reconstructs state from the repo) |
| `/consult "question"` | Delegate a hard decision / design / debugging call to the `advisor` agent — no model switch |
| `/unsupervised on\|off` | Toggle autonomous mode (no questions + proactive 90% pause) |
| `/auto-resume on\|off` | Toggle auto-recovery after a limit reset (independent of unsupervised) |
| `/pr [base]` | (optional) Open a PR — only when you want external review |
| `/workflow-decisions [setting]` | View/change a workflow setting |
| `/workflow-update` | Update the workflow plugin |

## Architecture

{{ARCHITECTURE_SUMMARY}}

Tech stack: {{TECH_STACK}}

Read on demand (not auto-loaded): `docs/dev/architecture.md`, `docs/workflow/` (lifecycle, quality, decisions, deploy).

**Preferences:** standing per-tech/feature recommendations — **not rules**; adapt to the project or reject with a stated reason. They live in `.claude/preferences/` (project) and `~/.claude/preferences/` (user-global; ephemeral in cloud, so put anything that must survive in the project), indexed by a non-auto-loaded `INDEX.md`. `/plan` folds matching ones into the spec; `/project-init`/`/project-onboard` install them. For ad-hoc work in a specialized area, read `INDEX.md` yourself first. Add one via "remember a preference for X".

## Models

**The session model never switches** — you stay on whatever you picked. Subagents do the tiered work: **Haiku** for mechanical/high-IO (`text-scout`, `runner`, `project-scaffolder`), **Sonnet/low** for the two needing light reasoning (`code-explorer`, `smoke-tester`), **best/high** read-only for `reviewer` and `advisor`. `/consult` delegates hard thinking to `advisor` instead of switching your model (a switch would blow the prompt cache). See Agents for when to use each.

## Agents — delegate proactively

Use automatically when they fit — don't ask first. Anything that reads many files or produces bulk output belongs in a subagent.

| Agent | Use when |
|-------|----------|
| `code-explorer` (Sonnet/low) | Understand code across >3-4 files, or "how does X work / where is it?" — orients via project docs, then targeted search; explains the flow, cites everything. Prefer over the built-in Explore |
| `text-scout` (Haiku) | Extract/summarize facts from a lot of text (code, logs, docs, big output) — "intelligent grep": a sourced digest, never invents |
| `runner` (Haiku) | Run the gate, a test suite, or the release script — reports pass/fail + key output, never fixes/judges |
| `smoke-tester` (Sonnet/low) | Manually exercise a running app from prose steps (blackbox — no spec/code) — reports failing steps only. Use at feature-done, pre-PR, or any user-facing check. Hand it **concrete, executable steps** (exact action + expected result) — it can't see the spec/code |
| `reviewer` (best/high) | Fresh-eyes review of a genuinely critical diff — read-only. Default is inline self-review |
| `advisor` (best/high) | Hard thinking on a briefed question — a decision, a design/debugging idea, unsure of approach. Driven by `/consult`; advises, never implements |

**One scout by default:** most questions need a single `code-explorer` or `text-scout`. Fan out several (driven from the main session — subagents can't spawn subagents) only for genuinely large codebases/corpora. Both cite every claim — rely only on what's sourced.

**A subagent can fail — never proceed on a missing result.** Re-run it (they're idempotent). If it fails again, ask (supervised) or write `## Blocked` (unsupervised).

## Skills — invoke proactively

**When a request matches a skill, invoke it — don't improvise a process a skill already covers.**

| User says… | Skill |
|-----------|-------|
| "capture this idea/bug" | `/draft` |
| "plan / spec out FEAT-001", "make X ready" | `/plan` |
| "implement / build FEAT-001" | `/implement` |
| "verify / does it actually work" | `/verify` |
| "commit" | `/commit` |
| "release / publish / bump version" | `/release` |
| "ship a version", "build these tickets", "work toward <topic>" | `/ship` |
| "resume / continue / I was interrupted" | `/resume` |
| "I'm stuck", a hard architecture/security call, want a design or debugging idea | `/consult` |
| "work on its own / stop asking me" | `/unsupervised on` |
| "keep going after the limit resets", "finish it while I'm away" | `/auto-resume on` |
| "open a PR / submit for review" | `/pr` (optional — default merges locally) |

Multiple tasks in one message: work through them in order; in unsupervised mode apply autonomous defaults and don't stop between them. `/ship` is the built-in orchestrator for a full cycle.

## Scope — build the whole ticket

The ticket's goal and acceptance criteria are the contract. **Never defer, stub, or mark "out of scope for later" anything the ticket requires** — core functionality, the hard part, a criterion, or the error/edge handling those criteria imply. Difficulty or size is not a reason to cut scope — that *is* the work; do it, `/consult` if stuck, or `## Blocked` if it truly needs a human. "Out of scope" is only for genuinely separable extras. If a ticket is too big, say so and split it with the user — never quietly ship the easy half.

## Merging

Default is **local git, no PR**: if the merge is fast-forward and the full gate already passed on this exact HEAD → `git merge --ff-only` (no re-run); otherwise resolve conflicts, re-run the full gate (`ci.sh full`), then merge. Merge commits carry `[skip ci]` unless the project is `ci-on-claude: yes`. Use `/pr` only for external review or if the repo requires it.

## GitHub via `gh`

The `gh` CLI is authenticated in **every** session, including cloud/web. When plain git fails at something GitHub-side (a proxy rejecting a tag/protected-branch push, a ref git can't create), **fall back to `gh` instead of giving up**: `gh api` for refs/tags (`gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/git/refs -f ref=refs/tags/vX -f sha=…`), `gh release`, `gh pr`, `gh run`. Cloud gotcha: the remote may be a proxy URL `gh` can't parse — pass **`-R {owner}/{repo}`** on `gh` subcommands.

## Documentation policy

Minimal and useful. Doc-comments only for function usage/params, class/file usage, and genuinely tricky algorithms/decisions. Keep one concise `docs/dev/architecture.md` (key decisions, algorithms, APIs, data model). User docs minimal — prefer self-explanatory UI + in-app hints over prose.

## Asking the user

When you need a decision, **ask in a plain chat message and wait** — do **not** use the `AskUserQuestion` tool. Batch related questions into one numbered list so the user answers in a single reply (this is how skills "ask up front"). In unsupervised mode, don't ask — apply the autonomous defaults and note assumptions.

## Session Behavior

- Session-start `=== AUTO-RESUME REQUIRED ===` → run `/resume` immediately.
- `=== IN-PROGRESS WORK FOUND ===` → tell the user, suggest `/resume`; don't auto-resume.
- `=== BLOCKED WORK ===` → surface the blocker; don't work around it.

**State lives in the repo** — branch + the in-progress spec's unchecked subtask boxes + `git log`. No checkpoint file; `/resume` reconstructs from these. Only branch notes: `## Blocked` (human needed) and `## Ship` (orchestration state).

**Two independent toggles** in `.claude/memory/settings.md`:
- **`unsupervised`** — *how* Claude works. `true`: never ask (apply the `/unsupervised` defaults), keep every subtask green-committed (an interruption loses at most the current subtask), write `## Blocked` + stop on a real blocker, post a short report when done. A usage-guard pause at the threshold (default 90%) → finish the atomic step, commit, end the turn. Supervised (default): still ask, run to the hard limit.
- **`auto_resume`** — *whether* an interrupted run wakes itself after a limit reset, in either mode. In cloud a recovery heartbeat (bound to the session) + the `auto-resume-guard.sh` hook keep it armed and tear it down when work is done — mechanics in `/auto-resume`. Locally the SessionStart hook / `scripts/claude-loop.sh` drives `/resume` on next start.
- **Coupling:** `/unsupervised on` turns `auto_resume` on too (an autonomous run must survive a limit kill); `off` leaves it on. Neither toggle changes whether Claude asks questions beyond the above.

## Memory

`.claude/memory/` holds project memory (decisions, gotchas, tech-debt — tracked) and runtime notes (gitignored). Read when relevant; not auto-loaded.

Runtime notes: `context-{branch}.md` for a branch's `## Blocked` note — **`{branch}` = the git branch with every `/` replaced by `-`** (`feature/feat-001-x` → `context-feature-feat-001-x.md`); hooks compute it this way, so skills must too. `/ship` state lives in the **fixed, branch-independent** `context-ship.md` (a ship spans many branches).
